initial_story: My observation is there exists unequal share of State monies with its residents, before all the Urban residents get defensive please hear me out. Presently no one except Corporations pay State income taxes. No individual pays state taxes. I noticed state funded bicycle paths, road maintenance, defunct Docks, powerful politicians pet projects such as office buildings, state troopers etc, etc. all these fundings and more are not necessary within City limits, I was amazed at how much our state provides city functions in the bigger cities thus growing the state budget, I saw on tv last night how adg&g was showing the little ones how to ice fish, couldn't the parents do that? yes I pay property taxes. But I will guarantee you once our City folk get the full bill with out the State monies we will not be as wasteful, on the office building...rent what space you need and help the office rental marked. In my business I just retired from,I would ask my managers, "how do you stop spending money"?
stories:
Here is the rephrased text:

My observation is that state funds are distributed unevenly among residents, and I'd like to explain before urban residents become defensive. Currently, only corporations pay state income taxes, while individuals do not. I've noticed that state-funded projects like bicycle paths, road maintenance, and politicians' pet projects, such as office buildings and state troopers, are not essential within city limits. These projects, along with others, contribute to the state budget's growth. I was surprised to see how much the state provides city services in larger cities. For instance, I saw a TV show teaching children how to ice fish, which made me wonder why parents couldn't do that. As someone who pays property taxes, I believe that if our city residents were fully responsible for their own expenses without state support, they would be more frugal. For example, instead of building an office building, rent only the needed space and help reduce office rental costs. In my former business, I would ask my managers, "How do you stop wasting money?"

I've observed that the range of municipal services provided by the state in large cities is extensive, but I wonder if they are truly necessary. As a property taxpayer, I think that if city residents were fully responsible for their expenses without state support, they would be more mindful of their spending. For example, instead of building an office, they might choose to rent the necessary space, thereby reducing costs.
